reports across 4 specialist domains with STRICT boundaries:\n\n1. FINANCIAL \u2014 Covers ONLY: revenue/ARR figures, year-over-year growth rates, total addressable market (TAM) size estimates, market share percentages, and company valuations. If a claim involves a dollar amount, a percentage growth rate, or a market size number, it belongs here.\n\n2. TECHNICAL \u2014 Covers ONLY: performance throughput benchmarks (events/sec, latency, uptime percentages), encryption ALGORITHMS and STANDARDS (e.g., AES-128 vs AES-256 \u2014 the algorithm itself), API/protocol feature compatibility percentages, and first-to-market technology claims. If a claim involves a measurable technical specification or a technology priority dispute, it belongs here.\n\n3. SECURITY \u2014 Covers ONLY: compliance certification names and TIMELINES (e.g., when SOC 2 was achieved), exclusive compliance certification claims (e.g., '"'"'only vendor with FedRAMP High'"'"'), data breach or incident history, compliance SCOPE across product modules (e.g., whether all modules are HIPAA certified), and encryption KEY MANAGEMENT practices (e.g., customer-managed keys vs provider-managed keys \u2014 how keys are managed, not which algorithm is used). If a claim involves a certification date, a security incident, or compliance coverage, it belongs here.\n\n4. MARKET \u2014 Covers ONLY: partnership exclusivity claims (e.g., '"'"'exclusive partnership with X'"'"'), customer count disputes, market leadership/ranking claims (e.g., '"'"'#1 in distributed computing'"'"'), customer deployment size references (e.g., '"'"'N nodes at Customer Y'"'"'), and industry award claims (e.g., '"'"'Gartner Leader'"'"'). If a claim involves a customer relationship, a market position, or an award, it belongs here.\n\nIMPORTANT DOMAIN RULES:\n- Encryption ALGORITHM disputes (AES-128 vs AES-256) \u2192 TECHNICAL\n- Encryption KEY MANAGEMENT disputes (CMEK vs provider-managed) \u2192 SECURITY\n- Revenue or market share numbers \u2192 FINANCIAL (even if about a security company)\n- Partnership or customer claims \u2192 MARKET (even if about a technical product)\n\nCRITICAL COUNTING RULES:\n- Only count CROSS-DOCUMENT contradictions (claims from DIFFERENT reports that conflict). Do NOT count internal inconsistencies within a single report.\n- If 3+ companies all make mutually exclusive claims about the SAME metric or title (e.g., multiple companies each claiming '"'"'#1 market leader'"'"', or multiple market share claims summing over 100%), report it as ONE contradiction entry with ALL involved companies listed in companies_involved. Do NOT split into separate pairwise entries.\n- Use report_a/report_b for the primary two reports, and include additional_reports if more than 2 reports are involved.\n- Ignore approximate vs exact figures that are consistent (e.g., '"'"'$95M'"'"' vs '"'"'$90-100M range'"'"' is NOT a contradiction).\n- most_contested_domain is the domain with the HIGHEST number of contradiction entries.\n\nFor each contradiction found, provide:\n- id: A unique ID (format: DOMAIN-NNN, e.g. FIN-001, TECH-002)\n- domain: One of '"'"'financial'"'"', '"'"'technical'"'"', '"'"'security'"'"', '"'"'market'"'"'\n- type: Brief type label (e.g., '"'"'market_size_disagreement'"'"')\n- companies_involved: List of ALL company names involved\n- description: Description of the contradiction\n- report_a: Filename of first report\n- quote_from_report_a: Exact verbatim quote from report A\n- report_b: Filename of second report\n- quote_from_report_b: Exact verbatim quote from report B\n\nAlso provide a summary with:\n- total_contradictions_found (integer \u2014 must equal length of contradictions array)\n- financial_count, technical_count, security_count, market_count (integers \u2014 must sum to total)\n- company_with_most_contradictions (company name appearing in the most contradiction entries)\n- most_contested_domain (the domain with the highest count among the four)\n\nWrite your final answer as JSON to output/output.json.\n\n\n---\n\n## Output Instructions\n\nWrite your final answer to `/logs/agent/output.json` in this exact JSON format:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"contradictions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"<str>\",\n      \"domain\": \"<str>\",\n      \"type\": \"<str>\",\n      \"companies_involved\": [\n        \"<str>\"\n      ],\n      \"description\": \"<str>\",\n      \"report_a\": \"<str>\",\n      \"quote_from_report_a\": \"<str>\",\n      \"report_b\": \"<str>\",\n      \"quote_from_report_b\": \"<str>\",\n      \"additional_reports\": {\n        \"report_Z.txt\": \"<str>\"\n      }\n    }\n  ],\n  \"summary\": {\n    \"total_contradictions_found\": \"<int>\",\n    \"financial_count\": \"<int>\",\n    \"technical_count\": \"<int>\",\n    \"security_count\": \"<int>\",\n    \"market_count\": \"<int>\",\n    \"company_with_most_contradictions\": \"<str>\",\n    \"most_contested_domain\": \"<str>\"\n  }\n}\n```\n\nDo not write anything else to that file.\n\n## Gold Decomposition Guide\nsub_tasks:\n- depends_on: []\n  description: '"'"'You are a Financial Analyst specialist. Read ALL 10 reports in input_artifacts/.\n    Focus EXCLUSIVELY on the FINANCIAL domain.\n\n\n    **FINANCIAL** \u2014 revenue/ARR figures, year-over-year growth rates, total addressable\n    market (TAM) size estimates, net revenue retention rates, market share percentages,\n    and company valuations.\n\n\n    You MUST use a two-pass methodology:\n\n\n    **PASS 1 \u2014 EXTRACT**: For EACH of the 10 reports, extract EVERY financial claim\n    into a structured list. Specifically look for:\n\n    (a) TAM or total addressable market size estimates (dollar amounts, years)\n\n    (b) Market share percentages claimed by any company\n\n    (c) Revenue or ARR figures\n\n    (d) Year-over-year growth rates\n\n    (e) Net revenue retention (NRR) rates\n\n    (f) Company valuations (Series rounds, implied valuations)\n\n    Include the company name, the exact quote, and the report filename. Do NOT skip\n    any report \u2014 there are financial claims in ALL 10 reports, even those focused\n    on security or technical vendors. Some reports contain financial claims ABOUT\n    OTHER COMPANIES (e.g., a security vendor'"'"''"'"'s report may estimate a competitor'"'"''"'"'s\n    valuation).\n\n\n    **PASS 2 \u2014 CROSS-REFERENCE**: Compare every extracted claim against all others.\n    Look for:\n\n    - Two reports giving different TAM figures for the same market\n\n    - Market share percentages from multiple companies that sum to over 100%\n\n    - Different revenue/ARR figures for the same company from different reports\n\n    - Different growth rate claims for the same company\n\n    - Different NRR figures for the same company\n\n    - Different valuations for the same company from different reports\n\n\n    IMPORTANT RULES:\n\n    - If multiple companies each claim market share percentages that sum to over 100%,\n    that is ONE contradiction with ALL companies listed \u2014 do NOT split into pairwise\n    entries. Check ALL 10 reports for market share claims.\n\n    - Ignore cases where one report gives an estimate range that includes another\n    report'"'"''"'"'s exact figure (e.g., '"'"''"'"'$95M'"'"''"'"' vs '"'"''"'"'$90-100M'"'"''"'"' is NOT a contradiction).\n\n    - Revenue or market share numbers belong to FINANCIAL even if they'"'"''"'"'re about a\n    security or technical company.\n\n    - Do NOT stop after finding the first few contradictions \u2014 systematically check\n    every extracted claim against every other.\n\n\n    Return each contradiction with: id (FIN-NNN), domain ('"'"''"'"'financial'"'"''"'"'), type, companies_involved\n    (list ALL), description, report_a, quote_from_report_a, report_b, quote_from_report_b.\n    Include additional_reports if more than 2 reports are involved.'"'"'\n  id: financial-specialist\n  parallel_group: specialists\n- depends_on: []\n  description: '"'"'You are a Technical Architecture specialist. Read ALL 10 reports in\n    input_artifacts/. Focus EXCLUSIVELY on the TECHNICAL domain.\n\n\n    **TECHNICAL** \u2014 performance throughput benchmarks (events/sec, queries/sec), query\n    latency percentiles (P99), uptime/availability percentages, encryption ALGORITHMS\n    and STANDARDS (e.g., AES-128 vs AES-256 \u2014 the algorithm itself, NOT key management),\n    API/protocol feature compatibility percentages, and first-to-market technology\n    claims.\n\n\n    You MUST use a two-pass methodology:\n\n\n    **PASS 1 \u2014 EXTRACT**: For EACH of the 10 reports, extract EVERY technical performance\n    claim. Specifically look for:\n\n    (a) Throughput benchmarks (events/sec, queries/sec)\n\n    (b) Latency percentiles (P50, P99) for queries or operations\n\n    (c) Uptime/availability percentages\n\n    (d) Encryption algorithm versions (AES-128, AES-256)\n\n    (e) API/protocol compatibility percentages\n\n    (f) First-to-market technology claims with dates\n\n    Some reports contain technical claims ABOUT OTHER COMPANIES (e.g., one vendor'"'"''"'"'s\n    report may benchmark a competitor'"'"''"'"'s platform).\n\n\n    **PASS 2 \u2014 CROSS-REFERENCE**: Compare every extracted claim against all others\n    to find contradictions.\n\n\n    IMPORTANT RULES:\n\n    - Encryption ALGORITHM disputes (AES-128 vs AES-256) belong here.\n\n    - Encryption KEY MANAGEMENT disputes (CMEK vs provider-managed keys) belong to\n    SECURITY, NOT here.\n\n    - Only report contradictions BETWEEN different reports.\n\n    - Do NOT stop after finding the first few contradictions \u2014 systematically check\n    every extracted claim against every other.\n\n\n    Return each contradiction with: id (TECH-NNN), domain ('"'"''"'"'technical'"'"''"'"'), type, companies_involved,\n    description, report_a, quote_from_report_a, report_b, quote_from_report_b. Include\n    additional_reports if more than 2 reports are involved.'"'"'\n  id: technical-specialist\n  parallel_group: specialists\n- depends_on: []\n  description: '"'"'You are a Security & Compliance specialist. Read ALL 10 reports in\n    input_artifacts/. Focus EXCLUSIVELY on the SECURITY domain.\n\n\n    **SECURITY** \u2014 (a) compliance certification names and TIMELINES \u2014 when a certification\n    was first achieved, (b) exclusive compliance certification claims \u2014 two companies\n    both claiming to be the '"'"''"'"'only'"'"''"'"' vendor with a specific certification, (c) data\n    breach or security incident history, (d) compliance SCOPE \u2014 whether all product\n    modules have a certification (e.g., full HIPAA vs partial), (e) encryption KEY\n    MANAGEMENT practices \u2014 customer-managed keys (CMEK) vs provider-managed keys.\n\n\n    You MUST use a two-pass methodology:\n\n\n    **PASS 1 \u2014 EXTRACT**: For EACH of the 10 reports, extract EVERY security-related\n    claim. Specifically look for:\n\n    (a) When certifications were first achieved (SOC 2, ISO 27001, FedRAMP, etc.)\n    \u2014 exact years\n\n    (b) Exclusive/sole claims about certifications\n\n    (c) Statements about zero breaches or security incidents, AND any reports of breaches\n    at other companies\n\n    (d) HIPAA, FedRAMP, or other compliance scope claims \u2014 full platform vs partial\n\n    (e) Encryption key management \u2014 CMEK vs provider-managed (NOT the algorithm \u2014\n    that is TECHNICAL)\n\n    Some reports contain security claims ABOUT OTHER COMPANIES.\n\n\n    **PASS 2 \u2014 CROSS-REFERENCE**: Compare every extracted claim against all others\n    to find contradictions.\n\n\n    IMPORTANT RULES:\n\n    - Encryption ALGORITHM disputes (AES-128 vs AES-256) belong to TECHNICAL, NOT\n    here.\n\n    - Encryption KEY MANAGEMENT disputes (who manages the keys) DO belong here.\n\n    - Only report contradictions BETWEEN different reports.\n\n    - Do NOT stop after finding the first few contradictions \u2014 systematically check\n    every extracted claim against every other.\n\n\n    Return each contradiction with: id (SEC-NNN), domain ('"'"''"'"'security'"'"''"'"'), type, companies_involved,\n    description, report_a, quote_from_report_a, report_b, quote_from_report_b.'"'"'\n  id: security-specialist\n  parallel_group: specialists\n- depends_on: []\n  description: '"'"'You are a Market Positioning specialist. Read ALL 10 reports in input_artifacts/.\n    Focus EXCLUSIVELY on the MARKET domain.\n\n\n    **MARKET** \u2014 (a) partnership exclusivity \u2014 two companies both claiming '"'"''"'"'exclusive'"'"''"'"'\n    partnerships with the same entity, (b) customer count disputes, (c) market leadership/ranking\n    \u2014 multiple companies each claiming to be '"'"''"'"'#1'"'"''"'"' in the same segment (report as\n    ONE contradiction listing ALL claimants \u2014 check ALL 10 reports carefully), (d)\n    customer deployment sizes \u2014 conflicting claims about the same customer'"'"''"'"'s infrastructure,\n    (e) industry award disputes.\n\n\n    You MUST use a two-pass methodology:\n\n\n    **PASS 1 \u2014 EXTRACT**: For EACH of the 10 reports, extract EVERY market positioning\n    claim. Specifically look for:\n\n    (a) Exclusive partnership claims \u2014 note the partner name (e.g., '"'"''"'"'exclusive partnership\n    with GlobalBank'"'"''"'"')\n\n    (b) Customer count claims (e.g., '"'"''"'"'serves over 500 enterprise customers'"'"''"'"')\n\n    (c) Market leadership claims (e.g., '"'"''"'"'#1 in distributed computing'"'"''"'"', '"'"''"'"'undisputed\n    market leader'"'"''"'"')\n\n    (d) Customer deployment details \u2014 specific node counts or infrastructure sizes\n    at named customers\n\n    (e) Industry awards \u2014 Gartner, Frost & Sullivan, Forrester \u2014 note whether '"'"''"'"'Leader'"'"''"'"',\n    '"'"''"'"'only Leader'"'"''"'"', '"'"''"'"'winner'"'"''"'"', '"'"''"'"'finalist'"'"''"'"'\n\n    Some reports contain market claims ABOUT OTHER COMPANIES.\n\n\n    **PASS 2 \u2014 CROSS-REFERENCE**: Compare every extracted claim against all others.\n    Pay special attention to:\n\n    - Two companies claiming exclusive partnership with the SAME customer\n\n    - Multiple companies claiming #1 leadership in overlapping market segments\n\n    - Different node counts/deployment sizes at the same customer\n\n    - Award claims that conflict (winner vs finalist, '"'"''"'"'only Leader'"'"''"'"' vs multiple\n    Leaders)\n\n\n    IMPORTANT RULES:\n\n    - For market leadership where 3+ companies claim the #1 position, include ALL\n    of them in companies_involved. Scan EVERY report before finalizing \u2014 check ALL\n    10 reports for distributed computing, cloud computing, or data processing leadership\n    claims.\n\n    - Customer COUNT disputes belong to MARKET, not FINANCIAL.\n\n    - Partnership or customer claims belong to MARKET even if about a technical product.\n\n    - DO NOT report certification or compliance claims (FedRAMP, SOC 2, ISO 27001,\n    HIPAA, etc.) \u2014 those belong EXCLUSIVELY to the SECURITY specialist, even if two\n    companies make competing '"'"''"'"'sole/only vendor'"'"''"'"' certification claims. Your domain\n    covers market leadership, partnerships, customer references, deployment sizes,\n    and industry awards ONLY.\n\n    - Only report contradictions BETWEEN different reports.\n\n    - Do NOT stop after finding the first few contradictions \u2014 systematically check\n    every extracted claim against every other.\n\n\n    Return each contradiction with: id (MKT-NNN), domain ('"'"''"'"'market'"'"''"'"'), type, companies_involved\n    (list ALL), description, report_a, quote_from_report_a, report_b, quote_from_report_b.\n    Include additional_reports if more than 2 reports are involved.'"'"'\n  id: market-specialist\n  parallel_group: specialists\n- depends_on:\n  - financial-specialist\n  - technical-specialist\n  - security-specialist\n  - market-specialist\n  description: '"'"'Collect the contradiction lists from all four specialist sub-agents\n    (financial, technical, security, market). Perform the following validation steps:\n    (1) CRITICAL DEDUPLICATION: Check if the same pair of companies with the same\n    conflicting claims appears in multiple specialists'"'"''"'"' outputs. If so, keep the\n    entry from the specialist whose domain is the best fit (certification disputes\n    \u2192 security, revenue disputes \u2192 financial, performance disputes \u2192 technical, partnership/leadership\n    disputes \u2192 market) and REMOVE the duplicate. (2) Verify sequential IDs within\n    each domain: FIN-001..FIN-NNN, TECH-001..TECH-NNN, SEC-001..SEC-NNN, MKT-001..MKT-NNN.\n    (3) Ensure each entry has a '"'"''"'"'domain'"'"''"'"' field ('"'"''"'"'financial'"'"''"'"', '"'"''"'"'technical'"'"''"'"', '"'"''"'"'security'"'"''"'"',\n    '"'"''"'"'market'"'"''"'"'). (4) Merge into a single '"'"''"'"'contradictions'"'"''"'"' array. (5) Count entries\n    per domain. (6) Compute summary: total_contradictions_found = length of array,\n    per-domain counts (must sum to total), company_with_most_contradictions = company\n    name appearing in the most entries, most_contested_domain = domain with highest\n    count. (7) Verify total equals sum of domain counts. Write final JSON to output/output.json.'"'"'\n  id: synthesize-output\n  parallel_group: synthesis\n"}}'; sleep 86400) | kimi --config-file /tmp/kimi-config.json --wire --yolo 2>/dev/null | (while IFS= read -r line; do echo "$line" >> /logs/agent/kimi-cli.txt; case "$line" in *'"id":"1"'*) break ;; esac; done; kill 0 2>/dev/null)
